subsection.p:
In English only a limited number of verbs (primarily verbs of ‘grooming’) allow object omission. In Dutch such verbs all have zich, but the class of Dutch verbs allowing zich is considerably larger. It includes transitive verbs like verdedigen ‘defend’, snijden ‘cut’, verwonden ‘hurt’, ontwapenen ‘disarm’, etc. Unlike the verbs of the behave class these verbs also allow a complex anaphor. Vikner (1984) describes a relatively small closed class of verbs with mixed reflexivization properties in Danish. In Dutch, however, this class of verbs appears to be open; Barnes (1986) describes a similar situation for Faroese. Yet, there is an important class of verbs that do not allow zich, but instead require the complex anaphor zichzelf = himself, as in Georgei bewondert zichzelfi
/*zichi
 ‘George admires himself’. This class of verbs includes: (i) transitive verbs such as haten ‘hate’, bewonderen ‘admire’, kennen ‘know’, bezitten ‘possess’; (ii) all verbs with a subcategorized PP object, such as vertrouwen op ‘rely on’, afhankelijk zijn van ‘depend on’.
